As daylight doth a lamp;her eyes in heaven As dearly as mine own, be satisfied. As glorious to this night, being o 'er my head, As he was coming from this churchyard side. DRAMATIS PERSONAE Dead art thou, dead! alack, my child is dead, Death is my son-in-law, Death is my heir;Death lies on her like an untimely frost Death, lie thou there, by a dead man interr 'd. Death, that hath suck 'd the honey of thy breath, Delay this marriage for a month, a week;Deny thy father and refuse thy name! Depart again. Here, here will I remain Despised substance of divinest show! Did ever dragon keep so fair a cave? Did murther her;as that name 's cursed hand Did my heart love till now? Forswear it, sight! Did not attend him as we rode? I think Digressing from the valour of a man;Direct my sail! On, lusty gentlemen! Displant a town, reverse a prince 's doom, Do I live dead that live to tell it now. Do as thou wilt, for I have done with thee. Exit. Do ebb and flow with tears;the bark thy body is Do lace the severing clouds in yonder East. Do thou but call my resolution wise Do thou but close our hands with holy words, Do you not see that I am out of breath? Doing more murther in this loathsome world, Dost thou love me, I know thou wilt say 'Ay';Dost thou not bring me letters from the friar? Dost thou not laugh? Doth add more grief to too much of mine own. Doth couch his limbs, there golden sleep doth reign. Doth grace for grace and love for love allow. Doth hurry from the fatal cannon 's womb. Doth make against me, of this direful murther;Doth much excuse the appertaining rage Doth my name lodge? Tell me, that I may sack Doth not she think me an old murtherer, Doth with their death bury their parents' strife. Doting like me, and like me banished, Dove-feather 'd raven! wolvish-ravening lamb! Down with the Capulets! Down with the Montagues! Drawn with a team of little atomies Driving back shadows over low 'ring hills. Drums in his ear, at which he starts and wakes, Dry sorrow drinks our blood. Adieu, adieu! Dry up your tears and stick your rosemary ESCALUS, Prince of Verona. Each part, depriv 'd of supple government, Earth-treading stars that make dark heaven light. Either be gone before the watch be set, Either my eyesight fails, or thou look 'st pale. Either thou or I, or both, must go with him. Either withdraw unto some private place Else would I tear the cave where Echo lies, Else would a maiden blush bepaint my cheek Else, when he is found, that hour is his last. Her Nurse is privy;and if aught in this Her blood is settled, and her joints are stiff;Her body sleeps in Capel 's monument, Her chariot is an empty hazelnut, Her collars, of the moonshine 's wat 'ry beams;Her eye discourses;I will answer it. Her mother is the lady of the house. Her traces, of the smallest spider 's web;Her vestal livery is but sick and green, Her wagon spokes made of long spinners' legs, Her wagoner, a small grey-coated gnat, Her whip, of cricket 's bone;the lash, of film;Here are the beetle brows shall blush for me. Take heed, take heed, for such die miserable. Take him and cut him out in little stars, Take it in what sense thou wilt. Take our good meaning, for our judgment sits Take thou some new infection to thy eye, Take thou this vial, being then in bed, Take up those cords. Poor ropes, you are beguil 'd, Taking the measure of an unmade grave. Taking thy part, hath rush 'd aside the law, Temp 'ring extremities with extreme sweet. Than death prorogued, wanting of thy love. Than empty tigers or the roaring sea. Than the death-darting eye of cockatrice. Than these poor compounds that thou mayst not sell. Than this of Juliet and her Romeo. Than those that have more cunning to be strange. Than thou went 'st forth in lamentation. Than twenty of their swords! Look thou but sweet, Than with that hand that cut thy youth in twain Than your consent gives strength to make it fly. Thank me no thankings, nor proud me no prouds, That God had lent us but this only child;That I have worn a visor and could tell That I might touch that cheek! That I must love a loathed enemy. That I reviv 'd and was an emperor. That I shall say good night till it be morrow. That I will show you shining at this feast, That I yet know not? That Romeo bid thee fetch? That Romeo should, upon receipt thereof, That after-hours with sorrow chide us not! That all the world will be in love with night That almost freezes up the heat of life. That 'banished,' that one word 'banished,' That birds would sing and think it were not night. That book in many 's eyes doth share the glory, That calls our person from our morning rest? That cop 'st with death himself to scape from it;That ever I should live to see thee dead! That ever ever I did yet behold! That fair for which love groan 'd for and would die, That gallant spirit hath aspir 'd the clouds, That he dares ne 'er come back to challenge you;That he shall soon keep Tybalt company;That he should hither come as this dire night That heaven finds means to kill your joys with love! That idles in the wanton summer air, That in gold clasps locks in the golden story;That in thy likeness thou appear to us! That is renown 'd for faith? Be fickle, Fortune, That late thou gavest me;for Mercutio 's soul That lets it hop a little from her hand, That living mortals, hearing them, run mad- That may convey my greetings, love, to thee. That monthly changes in her circled orb, That murd 'red me. I would forget it fain;That murd 'red my love 's cousin- with which grief That one short minute gives me in her sight. That pierc 'd the fearful hollow of thine ear. That plats the manes of horses in the night That presses them and learns them first to bear, That quench the fire of your pernicious rage That runaway eyes may wink, and Romeo That sees into the bottom of my grief? That shall she, marry;I remember it well. That she do give her sorrow so much sway, That slew thy kinsman, brave Mercutio. That the life-weary taker mall fall dead, That thou consent to marry us to-day. That thou expects not nor I look 'd not for. That thou hast done me;therefore turn and draw. That thou her maid art far more fair than she. That tips with silver all these fruit-tree tops- That unsubstantial Death is amorous, That villain cousin would have kill 'd my husband. That warns my old age to a sepulchre. That we have had no time to move our daughter. That we may call it early by-and-by. That were some spite;my invocation That westward rooteth from the city 's side, That whiles Verona by that name is known, That you are now a maid. Thus then in brief:That you run mad, seeing that she is well. That you shall all repent the loss of mine. That you shall rest but little. God forgive me! That 's by me wounded. Both our remedies That, when she dies, with beauty dies her store. Tybalt under Romeo 's arm thrusts Mercutio in. Tybalt, Mercutio, the Prince expressly hath Tybalt, liest thou there in thy bloody sheet? Tybalt, that murtherer, which way ran he? Tybalt, you ratcatcher, will you walk? Uncomfortable time, why cam 'st thou now Under love 's heavy burthen do I sink. Under yond yew tree lay thee all along, Uneven is the course;I like it not. Unfold the imagin 'd happiness that both Unless good counsel may the cause remove. Unless philosophy can make a Juliet, Unless that husband send it me from heaven Unless thou tell me how I may prevent it. Unplagu 'd with corns will have a bout with you. Unseemly woman in a seeming man! Unto my cell. Unto the rigour of severest law. Unto the white-upturned wond 'ring eyes Unwieldy, slow, heavy and pale as lead. Unworthy as she is, that we have wrought Up to the ears. Come, we burn daylight, ho! Upon a rapier 's point. Stay, Tybalt, stay! Upon his body that hath slaughter 'd him. Upon his brow shame is asham 'd to sit;Upon so soft a subject as myself! Upon the sweetest flower of all the field. Utter your gravity o 'er a gossip 's bowl, Verona. A churchyard;in it the monument of the CAPULETS. Verona. A public place. Verona. CAPULET 'S orchard. Verona. FRIAR LAURENCE 'S cell. Vile earth, to earth resign;end motion here, Virtue itself turns vice, being misapplied, Waking or sleeping, still my care hath been Warm and new kill 'd. Was Tybalt 's doomsday, whose untimely death Was ever book containing such vile matter Was stay 'd by accident, and yesternight Was that my father that went hence so fast? Was woe enough, if it had ended there;1. Watchman. A great suspicion! Stay the friar too. 3. Watchman. Here is a friar that trembles, sighs, and weeps. 1. Watchman. Here is a friar, and slaughter 'd Romeo 's man, 2. Watchman. Here 's Romeo 's man. We found him in the churchyard. 1. Watchman. Hold him in safety till the Prince come hither. 1. Watchman. Sovereign, here lies the County Paris slain;1 Watchman. 'the ground is bloody. Search about the churchyard. Watchman.[within.] Lead, boy. Which way? We are undone, lady, we are undone! We cannot without circumstance descry. We have a trifling foolish banquet towards. We met, we woo 'd, and made exchange of vow, We must talk in secret. Nurse, come back again;We see the ground whereon these woes do lie, We shall be much unfurnish 'd for this time. We sucking on her natural bosom find;We took this mattock and this spade from him We waste our lights in vain, like lamps by day. We would as willingly give cure as know. We 'll have no Cupid hoodwink 'd with a scarf, We 'll keep no great ado- a friend or two;We 'll measure them a measure, and be gone. Welcome from Mantua. What says Romeo? Welcome, gentlemen! I have seen the day Well said, my hearts!- You are a princox- go! Well, Juliet, I will lie with thee to-night. Were in a mask? Were of an age. Well, Susan is with God;Were thinly scattered, to make up a show. Wert thou as young as I, Juliet thy love, What I have spoke;but farewell compliment! What are they, I beseech your ladyship? What curious eye doth quote deformities? What cursed foot wanders this way to-night What doth her beauty serve but as a note What early tongue so sweet saluteth me? What further woe conspires against mine age? What here shall miss, our toil shall strive to mend. What if her eyes were there, they in her head? What if it be a poison which the friar What if this mixture do not work at all? What is her burying gave, that is her womb;What is it else? A madness most discreet, What is your will? What lady 's that, which doth enrich the hand What mean these masterless and gory swords What said my man when my betossed soul What say you, Simon Catling? What say 'st thou? Hast thou not a word of joy? What says he of our marriage? What of that? What simpleness is this.- I come, I come![Knock.] What sorrow craves acquaintance at my hand What torch is yond that vainly lends his light What unaccustom 'd cause procures her hither? What 's Montague? it is nor hand, nor foot, What 's here? A cup, clos 'd in my true love 's hand? What 's in a name? That which we call a rose What, dress 'd, and in your clothes, and down again? What, goodman boy? I say he shall. Go to! What, have you din 'd at home? What, is my daughter gone to Friar Laurence? What, not a word? You take your pennyworths now! What, rouse thee, man! Thy Juliet is alive, What, wilt thou wash him from his grave with tears? What, with a torch? Muffle me, night, awhile. Whate 'er thou hearest or seest, stand all aloof When I, thy three-hours wife, have mangled it? When King Cophetua lov 'd the beggar maid! When but love 's shadows are so rich in joy. 'When griping grief the heart doth wound, When he bestrides the lazy-pacing clouds When it did taste the wormwood on the nipple When it hoars ere it be spent. When presently through all thy veins shall run When theirs are dry, for Romeo 's banishment. When thou didst bower the spirit of a fiend When well apparell 'd April on the heel Where I may read who pass 'd that passing fair? Where Juliet lives;and every cat and dog Where all the kindred of the Capulets lie. Where and what time thou wilt perform the rite;Where be these enemies? Capulet, Montage, Where bloody Tybalt, yet but green in earth, Where civil blood makes civil hands unclean. Where for this many hundred years the bones Where is my father and my mother, nurse? Where is my lady 's lord, where 's Romeo? Where is my page? Go, villain, fetch a surgeon. Where is she? and how doth she! and what says Where is the County 's page that rais 'd the watch? "Where is your mother?"' Where on a sudden one hath wounded me Where serpents are;chain me with roaring bears, Where shall we dine? O me! What fray was here? Where should she be? How oddly thou repliest! Where that same banish 'd runagate doth live, Where the infectious pestilence did reign, Where thou shalt live till we can find a time Where 's Romeo 's man? What can he say in this? Where, underneath the grove of sycamore Whereto I have invited many a guest, Which are the children of an idle brain, Which craves as desperate an execution Which heavy sorrow makes them apt unto. Which is as thin of substance as the air, Which is the god of my idolatry, Which mannerly devotion shows in this;Which modern lamentation might have mov 'd? Which oft the angry Mab with blisters plagues, Which once untangled much misfortune bodes Which she hath prais 'd him with above compare Which should bedeck thy shape, thy love, thy wit. Which ten times faster glide than the sun 's beams Which the commission of thy years and art Which the dark night hath so discovered. Which then most sought where most might not be found, Which thou wilt propagate, to have it prest Which to the high topgallant of my joy Which too untimely here did scorn the earth. Which with sweet water nightly I will dew, Which you weep for. Which you, mistaking, offer up to joy. Which, as he breath 'd defiance to my ears, Which, as they kiss, consume. The sweetest honey Which, but their children 's end, naught could remove, Which, like a usurer, abound 'st in all, Which, on more view of many, mine, being one, Which, too much minded by herself alone, Which, well thou knowest, is cross and full of sin. While we were interchanging thrusts and blows, Whipp 'd and tormented and- God-den, good fellow. Whiter than new snow upon a raven 's back. Who ever would have thought it? Romeo! Who had but newly entertain 'd revenge, Who here hath lain this two days buried. Who is already sick and pale with grief Who knocks so hard? Whence come you? What 's your will? Who now the price of his dear blood doth owe? Who, all as hot, turns deadly point to point, Who, even in pure and vestal modesty, Who, nothing hurt withal, hiss 'd him in scorn. Who, raging with thy tears and they with them, Whose misadventur 'd piteous overthrows Whose names are written there, and to them say, Whose sale is present death in Mantua, Why I descend into this bed of death Why art thou yet so fair? Shall I believe Why followed not, when she said 'Tybalt 's dead,' Why railest thou on thy birth, the heaven, and earth? Why should you fall into so deep an O?[He rises] Why 'silver sound'? Why 'music with her silver sound'? Why then, O brawling love! O loving hate! Why, lamb! why, lady! Fie, you slug-abed! Why, love, I say! madam! sweetheart! Why, bride! Wife, go you to her ere you go to bed;Will I set up my everlasting rest Will ne 'er wear out the everlasting flint. Will now deny to dance? She that makes dainty, Will they not hear? What, ho! you men, you beasts, Will watch thy waking, and that very night Will you be ready? Do you like this haste? Will you go to them? I will bring you thither. Wilt thou not, Jule?' It stinted, and said 'Ay.' Wilt thou not, Jule?' and, by my holidam, With Cupid 's arrow. She hath Dian 's wit, With Romeo till I behold him- dead- With Tybalt 's slander- Tybalt, that an hour With all the admired beauties of Verona. With baleful weeds and precious-juiced flowers. With blood remov 'd but little from her own? With gentle breath, calm look, knees humbly bow 'd- With instruments upon them fit to open With more of thine. This love that thou hast shown With nimble soles;I have a soul of lead With open outcry, toward our monument. With piercing steel at bold Mercutio 's breast;With purple fountains issuing from your veins! With reeky shanks and yellow chapless skulls;With repetition of my Romeo 's name. With speedy help doth lend redress.'[Exit.] With tears augmenting the fresh morning 's dew, With tender Juliet match 'd, is now not fair.
